The rules of prosody, as commonly taught, must be con- siderably modified, if we are to understand the scansion of Plautus and Terence. It must always be remembered that the poets of the late days of the Republic and their successors were writing in a literary language, not in the language of every- day life. The quantity of any syllable was regarded as rigidly fixed, just as we might find it marked in a dictionary. In reading the cornic poets we find that not merely the word itself, but its relation to other words is important. We have to consider accent as well as quantity; for a remarkable instance cf. 760, where we find mane, cava.
